Quick tip in case anyone is facing this issue when setting up a drive based federated source to BQ via Apps Script. Enabling the Drive API in the UI won't be enough. In case the app doesn't explicitly call any Drive related API calls, the drive scope won't get added into the script. 

This worked in my case by explicitly enabling the drive scope in the manifest.json file (make sue to select  "show manifest file" in the UI). The scope for drive is https://www.googleapis.com/auth/drive to be added into the *oauthScopes* list, example:

```
{
  "timeZone": "Asia/Dubai",
  "oauthScopes": [
    "https://www.googleapis.com/auth/drive",
    "https://www.googleapis.com/auth/bigquery",
    "https://www.googleapis.com/auth/spreadsheets"
  ],
  "dependencies": {
    "enabledAdvancedServices": [{
      "userSymbol": "Drive",
      "serviceId": "drive",
      "version": "v3"
    }, {
      "userSymbol": "BigQuery",
      "serviceId": "bigquery",
      "version": "v2"
    }]
  },
  "webapp": {
    "access": "MYSELF",
    "executeAs": "USER_DEPLOYING"
  },
  "exceptionLogging": "STACKDRIVER"
}

```
**Disclaimer: This is not an official solution from Google. It worked for my specific individual use case and it might (or not) work for yours. No warranties given, use and test at your own risk.**

@darkskiez agreed. I think it was late with not enough coffee, since there is no way to pass an optional argument to a property anyway. *facepalm*.

@christiandt So, my lack of caffeine induced errors aside. My suggestions would be:

 * From the getter return None if the mode is not supported
 * In the setter raise a custom NotSupported exception (which you will have to add to exceptions) if the mode is not supported

I would prefer not to add the is_playbar property at this point. I already regret that we have three properties for `is_playing_tv`, `is_playing_radio`, `is_playing_line_in` instead of one is_playing that returns strings. I think the same applies here. The information is already exposed via `get_speaker_info`, however if it is really important we could think about translating them and serving them as nice clean strings through a `player_type` or similar, but I think that should be a separate PR.

So if you can move the check semantics into the properties (get and setter) I think we are good to go.

